% argument
Building on the fiscal sociology paradigm, I argue that the implementation of the income tax contributed to form the Latin American state. In turn, the income tax was product of an inter-sectoral conflict between agricultural and industrial elites (see \autoref{causal:mechanism:fig}). 


Schumpeter argued in favor of a systematic study of public finances, treating taxation both as cause (and consequence) of large-scale changes in the structure of the state.\footnote{Martin et al. (in \citet[2]{Martin2009a}).} Famously, he argued that `the budget is the skeleton of the state stripped of all misleading ideologies.'\footnote{\citet[100]{Schumpeter:1991yq}.} I contend that the expansion of the fiscal system, embodied specially in the income tax, contributed in an important way to the consolidation of the Latin American state. `Tax states' penetrate individual economies\footnote{\citet[298]{Moore2004a}.}, transforming private income into public property.\footnote{\citet[98]{Musgrave1992}.} As they do, states 











