Since taxing incomes involves 

According to the fiscal sociology approach, the great modern cleavage was not the rise of capitalism (Marx) nor the rise of modern bureaucracy (Weber), but the rise of the ``tax state,'' which developed institutions to penetrate individual economies.\footnote{\citet[298]{Moore2004a}. See epigraphs ( and \citet[42]{Lewis:1965nr}).} 






 The income tax was both a product \emph{and} a consequence of sustained economic growth, but particularly, \emph{industrial} growth. Faster industrial output nurtured a new demanding political elite, leading to a string of institutional investments, setting countries in a long-term path of state-building. Tilly defines state capacity as ``the extent to which interventions of state agents in existing non-state resources [such as wages] alter existing distributions of those resources.''\footnote{In \citet[173]{Martin2009a}.} It is this `meddling' what cause a state to develop. For example, \citet[99]{Musgrave1992} argues that since taxation (specially on incomes) requires such a high degree of state penetration, public finances offer the key for a theory of state-building. 


The fiscal sociology paradigm is vast.\footnote{For an excellent overview of both classic and new fiscal sociology refer to \citet[Ch. 1]{Martin2009a}.} Without trying to survey all of it, 

This paper follows the classical approach famously suggested by Schumpeter in that it sees ``taxation in terms of group conflicts [and] class interests.''\footnote{\citet[14]{Monson2015}.} Similarly, Seligman in 1895 argued that ``[f]iscal conditions are always an outcome of economic relations,''\footnote{In \citet[7]{Martin2009a}.} while Goldscheid in 1925 famously argued that ``tax struggles are among the oldest forms of class struggle.''\footnote{In \citet[168]{Campbell1993}.} This paper is situated within this tradition, emphasizing the sectoral conflicts between two elites invested in different assets in Latin America. State-making depends on conflict. As others have argued, ``state formation will be more likely to the degree that powerful individual actors form two groups on the basis of divergent economic and political interests.''\footnote{\citet[1085]{Hechter1980a}.} And the conflict is sectoral in nature. State centralization affects landowners and industrialists in different ways.\footnote{\citet[289]{Acemoglu:1996rm}.} Agriculturalists systematically resisted taxation as land fixity increased the risk premium of their main asset,\footnote{\citet[512]{Robinson2006a}.} while industrialists' preferences toward taxation were more elastic as capital could be reinvested in nontaxable sectors.\footnote{\citet[]{Hirschman:1970bl} and Ronald Rogowski in \citet[ch. 4]{Drake:1998pi}. However, see \citet[15]{Bates1985}.} Taxation has always been conflictual since it has an important coercive element. As Martin et al. argue ``a tax is not a fee paid in direct exchange for a service, but rather an obligation to contribute.''\footnote{in \citet[3]{Martin2009a}.} What makes taxation relevant, conflictual and coercive is not the tribute itself (and the potential promise of provision of public goods), but its compulsoriness. Regardless of an individual's race, religion, culture or any other kind of status, the state classifies its subjects according to their incomes and oblige them to pay, punishing whoever refuses to do so. From a sociological standpoint, this ``generality makes taxation a crucial element in the development of the `imagined community' (\citet[]{Anderson2006a}) of the modern nation-state [...] Taxation enmeshes us in the web of generalized reciprocity that constitutes modern society.''\footnote{Martin et al. (in \citet[3]{Martin2009a}).}




